First of all, use of *`&lt;% scriptlets %&gt;`* is deprecated in JSPs so consider switching to JSP EL. I&#39;ve used the same to show how simple its use is.

To retrieve `price` in the other JSP, you have to pass it too. Currently, your `&lt;select&gt;` displays both `name` and `price`, but passes `name` only. So, the JSP code should look like

    &lt;c:set var=&quot;names&quot; value=&quot;&lt;%= name %&gt;&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;c:set var=&quot;prices&quot; value=&quot;&lt;%= price %&gt;&quot; /&gt;
    
    &lt;select name=&quot;food&quot; multiple=&quot;multiple&quot; size=&quot;10&quot; &gt;
      &lt;c:forEach items=&quot;${names}&quot; var=&quot;name&quot; varStatus=&quot;loop&quot;&gt;
        &lt;option value=&quot;${name}=${prices[loop.index]}&quot;&gt;
            ${name}-------- $${prices[loop.index]}
        &lt;/option&gt; 
      &lt;/c:forEach&gt;
    &lt;/select&gt;

In your target servlet you can retrieve the *name=price* mappings and store it in whicever way is more convenient for your JSP to retrive the values from. I&#39;m storing the values in a `Map` here.

    String[] selection = request.getParameterValues(&quot;food&quot;);
    
    Map&lt;String, String&gt; foodPrices = new HashMap&lt;String, String&gt;(selection.length);
    for (String option: selection) {
        String[] foodPrice = option.split(&quot;=&quot;);
        foodPrices.put(foodPrice[0], foodPrice[1]);
    }
    
    application.setAttribute(&quot;foodMap&quot;, foodPrices);

Now, in your JSP you can access the prices as

    &lt;c:forEach items=&quot;${foodMap}&quot; var=&quot;entry&quot;&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;Price of ${entry.key} = $${entry.value}&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/c:forEach&gt;

By the way, I&#39;m not sure if you should store the user&#39;s food selection into `application` scope as its shared by all the users of your application. If that&#39;s not what you intended, use the `session` scope instead.

